%[text] # Base estimators
%[text] 
%[text] Tutorial file for showcasing plain BVARs, and their most important actions
%[text] - Estimation
%[text] - Unconditional forecast with reduced form models
%[text] - Types of structural identification
%[text] - Impulse responses
%[text] - Historical structural shock decomosition
%[text] - Structural shock decomposition of unconditional forecast
%[text] - FEVD
%[text] - Conditional forecast \
%[text] ## Housekeeping
clear
close all
  
import base.*
%%
%[text] ## Convenience functions
%[text] The `extremesFunc` function compresses any number of samples (draws from the posterior) into two numbers - the minimum and the maximum.
percentiles = [10, 50, 90];

prctileFunc = @(x) prctile(x, percentiles, 2);

extremesFunc = @(x) [min(x, [], 2), max(x, [], 2)];

medianFunc = @(x) median(x, 2);

flatFunc = @(x) x(:, :);

defaultColors = get(0, "defaultAxesColorOrder");

%%
%[text] ## Number of Samples
numPresampled = 100;
%%
%[text] ## Prepare meta information for the models
%[text] 
%[text] Note that the meta information are common to all plain BVAR models, regardless of the specific estimator used.
%[text] The properties specific to all BVARs are the followings:
%[text] **endogenousNames** – list of endogenous variables
%[text] **exogenousNames** – list of exogenous variables
%[text] **order** – order, number of lags 
%[text] **intercept** – logical variable; set to **"**`true`**"** to include an intercept, or **"**`false`**"** for models without a constant term.
%[text] **estimationSpan** – the time range over which the model is estimated.
%[text] **identificationHorizon** – the maximum length of the identification period, corresponding to the length of the structural impulse responses.
%[text] **shockNames** – user-defined names of structural shocks. If not specified, the endogenous variables’ names are used with the suffix `_shock`.


estimStart = datex.q(1975,1);
estimEnd = datex.q(2014,4);
estimSpan = datex.span(estimStart, estimEnd);

meta = Meta( ...
    endogenousNames=["DOM_GDP", "DOM_CPI", "STN"], ...
    exogenousNames="Oil", ...
    order=4, ...
    intercept=true, ...
    estimationSpan=estimSpan, ...
    identificationHorizon=12, ...
    shockNames=["DEM", "SUP", "POL"] ...
);

%%
%[text] ## Specifying and loading input data
inputTbl = tablex.fromFile("data/exampleData.csv");
dataH = DataHolder(meta, inputTbl);
%%
%[text] ## Reduced form models
%[text] There are several common hyperparameters for plain BVARs, mainly the hyperparameters. The default values are given in the brackets.
%[text] **Autoregression (0.8)** –  prior mean on the first own lag
%[text] **Lambda1 (0.1)** – Controls the overall degree of shrinkage toward the prior mean.
%[text] **Lambda2 (0.5)** – Adjusts the relative tightness across equations, scaling by variable variance.
%[text] **Lambda3 (1)** –  Lag decay, governs how rapidly the prior tightness decreases with increasing lag order.
%[text] **Lambda4 (100)** –  Determines the tightness applied to coefficients of exogenous regressors.
%[text] **Lambda5 (1/100)** –  Controls the shrinkage on block exogenous components.
%[text] **Exogenous (false)** –  Contoling whether to use prior on exgenous variables
%[text] 
%[text] 
%[text] ### Basic BVARs
%[text] 
%[text] However, there are also some estimator-specific settings. All settings—both common and specific—can be overridden by providing new values for these options when configuring the estimator, as demonstrated in the `Minnesota` example below
%[text] 
%[text] #### **Ordinary**
%[text] **Important note** – mainly usage is to combine this with dummy observation e.g Minnesota 
% estimatorR1 = estimator.Ordinary(meta)
%[text] 
%[text] #### **Minnesota priors**
%[text] Estimator sepcific settings:
%[text] **Sigma (ar)** – controls the priors used for calculating the covariance matrix. Possible values are:
%[text] - **ar** – uses the variances matrix from estimated AR models foer each variable (with the same order as the final model),
%[text] - **diag** – uses only the diagonal elements of the covariance matrix from an estimated VAR (with the same order as the final model),
%[text] - **full** – uses the full covariance matrix from an estimated VAR (with the same order as the final model) \
estimatorR1 = estimator.Minnesota(meta, Sigma = "diag", Autoregression = 1) %[output:2b5e6dea]
%[text] #### 
%[text] #### **Normal Wishart priors**
%[text] Estimator specific settings:
%[text] **Sigma (ar)** – controls the priors used for calculating the covariance matrix. Possible values are:
%[text] - **ar** – uses the variances matrix from estimated AR models for each variable (with the same order as the final model),
%[text] - **eye** – using the identity matrix \
% estimatorR1 = estimator.NormalWishart(meta)
%[text] #### 
%[text] #### **Normal Diffuse prior**
%[text] There are no estimator-specific settings other than the hyperparameters.
% estimatorR1 = estimator.NormalDiffuse(meta)
%[text] #### 
%[text] #### **Individual Normal Wishart prior**
%[text] Estimator sepcific settings:
%[text] **Sigma (ar)** – controls the priors used for calculating the covariance matrix. Possible values are:
%[text] - **ar** – uses the variances matrix from estimated AR models foer each variable (with the same order as the final model),
%[text] - **eye** – using the identity matrx \
% estimatorR1 = estimator.IndNormalWishart(meta)
%[text] #### 
%[text] #### **Flat priors**
%[text] There are no estimator-specific settings other than the hyperparameters.
% estimatorR1 = estimator.Flat(meta)
%[text] ### 
%[text] ### Stochastic volatility (SV) BVARs - SV models from BEAR5
%[text] 
%[text] Note that SV models for large shocks will be discussed in a separate tutorial
%[text] All SV models in this group (including the general time varying model) share the same estimator specific settings
%[text] **HeteroskedasticityAutoRegression** – prior on the autoregression in heteroskedasticity (gamma in BEAR5)
%[text] **HeteroskedasticityShape** – prior on the shape of the inverse gamma distribution of the variance of the residual in heteroskedasticity (alpha in BEAR5)
%[text] **HeteroskedasticityScale** – prior on the scale of the inverse gamma distribution of the variance of the residual in heteroskedasticity (delta in BEAR5)
%[text] 
%[text] #### Standard SV model ( Cogley and Sargent (2005) )
% estimatorR1 = estimator.CogleySargentSV(meta)
%[text] #### 
%[text] #### SV model with Random Inertia 
%[text] 
%[text] **HeteroskedasticityAutoRegressionVariance** – prior on the variance of the autoregression in heteroskedasticity (zeta0 in BEAR5)
% estimatorR1 = estimator.RandomInertiaSV(meta)
%[text] #### 
%[text] #### SV model for large Bayesian VAR ( Carriero et al. (2012) )
% estimatorR1 = estimator.CarrieroSV(meta)
%[text] ### 
%[text] ### Time-varying (TV) BVARs
%[text] 
%[text] #### **Time varying dynamic parameters only**
%[text] There are no estimator-specific settings other than the hyperparameters.
% estimatorR1 = estimator.BetaTV(meta)
%[text] #### 
%[text] #### **Time varying dynamic parameters and stochastic volatility**
%[text] As mentioned above the common SV setings could be applied here as well
% estimatorR1 = estimator.GeneralTV(meta)
%%
%[text] ## Creating dummy observations
%[text] 
%[text] The majority of the reduced form estimators could be combined by dummy observations, the feature could be tested by 
estimatorR1.CanHaveDummies %[output:6079a076]
%[text] ### 
%[text] Each dummy observation has its own overla tightness hyperparameter **Lambda,** however its default value differs across dummies.
%[text] ### Sum of coefficients dummy
%[text] 
%[text] Dummy specific hyperparameters
%[text] **Lambda (0.1)** 
sumCoeffD = dummies.SumCoeff(Lambda=1e-4);
sumCoeffD.Lambda %[output:1e6ad39b]
%[text] 
%[text] ### **Initial observation dummy**
%[text] 
%[text] Dummy specific hyperparameters
%[text] **Lambda (0.001)** 
initObsD = dummies.InitialObs();
%[text] ### 
%[text] ### **Minnesota dummy**
%[text] 
%[text] Dummy specific hyperparameters
%[text] **Lambda (0.1)** 
%[text] **LagDecay (1)**  –  Lag decay, governs how rapidly the prior tightness decreases with increasing lag order. 
%[text] **Autoregression (0.8**)   –   Prior mean on the first own lag
%[text] **ExogenousLambda (100)**   –   Determines the tightness applied to coefficients of exogenous regressors.
%[text] **Exogenous (false)** –  Controlling whether to use prior on exogenous variables
minnesotaD = dummies.Minnesota();
%[text] 
%[text] ## Long-run dummies
%[text] Dummy specific hyperparameters
%[text] **Lambda (1)**
%[text] Note that for this dummz the long run relationships should be added as an input table or matrix.
longRunTbx = tablex.forLongRunDummies(meta);
longRunTbx{"DOM_GDP", "DOM_GDP"} = 1;
longRunTbx{"DOM_CPI", "DOM_CPI"} = 1;
longRunTbx{"DOM_CPI", "STN"} = 1;
longRunTbx{"STN", "DOM_CPI"} = -1;
longRunTbx{"STN", "STN"} = 1;

longRunD = dummies.LongRun(Table=longRunTbx,Lambda=1e-4);
longRunD.Lambda %[output:1d40609d]
longRunD.Table %[output:1ddc8e75]
%[text] 
%[text] 
%%
%[text] ## Creating the reduced form model
%[text] 

modelR1 = ReducedForm( ...
    meta=meta ...
    , dataHolder=dataH ...
    , estimator=estimatorR1 ...
);

%[text] 
%[text] ### Adding dummy observations
%[text] 
%[text] Users can also add the dummy observations created above to the reduced-form estimator as shown below. Combining multiple dummies is also allowed.
% modelR1 = ReducedForm( ...
%     meta=meta ...
%     , dataHolder=dataH ...
%     , estimator=estimatorR1 ...
%     , dummies={initObsD, minnesotaD}
% );
%[text] 
%%
%[text] ## Estimation/sampling of the reduced form model 

modelR1.initialize();
info0 = modelR1.presample(numPresampled); %[output:7a54578a]
modelR1.Presampled{1}.beta %[output:777fa3ed]

%%
%[text] ## Running Unconditional forecast 
%[text] 
%[text] ### Setting up the forecast range and run the forecast
fcastStart = datex.shift(modelR1.Meta.EstimationEnd, -10); %The forecast starts 10 periods prior to the end of the estimation span.
fcastEnd = datex.shift(modelR1.Meta.EstimationEnd, 0); %The forecast ends at the end of the estimation window.
fcastSpan = datex.span(fcastStart, fcastEnd);

fcastStart, fcastEnd %[output:765993c5] %[output:45452a2e]

fcastTbx = modelR1.forecast(fcastSpan);
fcastPrctileTbx = tablex.apply(fcastTbx, prctileFunc);
fcastPrctileTbx = tablex.flatten(fcastPrctileTbx); %keeping only the pctiles set at the beginning of the file (10, 50, 90)


%[text] ### Visualize the unconditional forecast
chartpack.forecastPercentiles( ... %[output:group:6ac4ae8d] %[output:8e98373d] %[output:70f805e1] %[output:6c3e7c8d] %[output:2f0589d4]
    fcastPrctileTbx, modelR1, FigureTitle ="Unconditional forecast") %[output:group:6ac4ae8d] %[output:8e98373d] %[output:70f805e1] %[output:6c3e7c8d] %[output:2f0589d4]
%%
%[text] ## Identification
%[text] 
%[text] ### Cholesky
%[text] You can use the Cholesky decomposition also with a different ordering of endogenous variables than in the meta specification. However, if the trailing part of the order matches the meta order, you may omit that portion.
%[text] 
%[text] #### Setting up the identifier

identChol = identifier.Cholesky(ordering=["DOM_CPI", "DOM_GDP", "STN"]); %reordering the variables

modelS1 = Structural(reducedForm=modelR1, identifier=identChol);
modelS1.initialize();

info0 = modelS1.presample(numPresampled); %[output:79158003]
modelS1.Presampled{1} %[output:5ee4b8af]
%[text] #### 
%[text] #### Checking transition matrices
modelS1.Presampled{1}.IdentificationDraw %[output:3b1283ba]
modelS1.Presampled{1}.IdentificationDraw.A{1,1} %[output:109577a5]
modelS1.Presampled{1}.IdentificationDraw.A{2,1} %[output:46493e10]
%[text] #### 
%[text] #### Checking scaling matrix
modelS1.Presampled{1}.D %[output:64aeda78]
modelS1.Presampled{2}.D %[output:8c52b83e]
%[text] ### 
%[text] ### Instant zeros restrictions
%[text] #### 
%[text] #### Specify instant zero restrictions 
%[text] - Create an empty table for instant zero restrictions using `tablex.forInstantZeros`
%[text] - The table has endogenous variables in rows, shocks in columns
%[text] - Fill in zeros for the elements to be restricted
%[text] - The algorithm can only handle \*underdetermined\* systems, meaning it must have at least one "degree of freedom"; this means the max number of zero restrictions is  `n * (n-1) / 2 - 1`
%[text] - The algorithm is able handle an edge case of no restrictions - it simply produces fully randomized unconstrained factors of the covariance matrix \

instantZerosTbl = tablex.forInstantZeros(modelR1);
instantZerosTbl{"DOM_CPI", "DEM"} = 0;
instantZerosTbl{"STN", "SUP"} = 0;
instantZerosTbl %[output:563e73ce]

tablex.writetable(instantZerosTbl, "data/instantZerosTbl.xlsx");
instantZerosTbl = tablex.readtable("data/instantZerosTbl.xlsx", convertTo=@double);
%[text] ### 
%[text] #### Seting up the identifier
identInstantZeros = identifier.InstantZeros(table=instantZerosTbl);

modelS2 = Structural(reducedForm=modelR1, identifier=identInstantZeros);
modelS2.initialize();
info1 = modelS2.presample(numPresampled); %[output:838699e1]
modelS2.Presampled{1} %[output:3cc20bdc]
%[text] #### 
%[text] #### Checking transition matrices
modelS2.Presampled{1}.IdentificationDraw %[output:80b63ce4]
modelS2.Presampled{1}.IdentificationDraw.A{1,1} %[output:096d1985]
modelS2.Presampled{1}.IdentificationDraw.A{2,1} %[output:6ee954b5]
%[text] #### 
%[text] #### Checking scaling matrix
modelS2.Presampled{1}.D %[output:3692080d]
modelS2.Presampled{2}.D %[output:0aee30cb]
%[text] ### 
%[text] ### General restrictions
%[text] #### 
%[text] #### Specify restrictions
%[text] 
%[text] General restrictions are strings representing an expression that evaluates to `true` or `false`, using the following references to "system properties"
%[text] - `\\$SHKRESP` — shock responses
%[text] - `\\$FEVD` — forecast variance contributions
%[text] - `\\$SHKCONT` — histrorical shock contributions
%[text] - `\\$SHKEST` — histroical estimated shocks  \
%[text] Each restriction should be included as a string element in a vector defining the desired restrictions for the structural VAR
%[text] 
%[text] #### **Restriction on simulation properties**
%[text] For shock responses (`\\$SHKRESP`) and forecast error variance (`\\$FEVD`), each element in the vector represents one restriction and should specify:
%[text] - the **period**,
%[text] - the **endogenous variable**,
%[text] - the **shock name**, and
%[text] - the **expected sign or magnitude** of the response/contribution. \
%[text] The general syntax follows the pattern:
%[text] `"\\$SHKRESP(period, 'endogenousName', 'shockName') >/< X"`
%[text] `"\\$FEVD(period, 'endogenousName', 'shockName') >/< X"`
signStrings = [ %[output:group:6bc102d0] %[output:7e33eb56]
    "$SHKRESP(2, 'DOM_GDP', 'DEM') > 0" %[output:7e33eb56]
    "$SHKRESP(2, 'DOM_CPI', 'DEM') > 0" %[output:7e33eb56]
%[output:7e33eb56]
    "$SHKRESP(3, 'DOM_GDP', 'DEM') > 0" %[output:7e33eb56]
    "$SHKRESP(3, 'DOM_CPI', 'DEM') > 0" %[output:7e33eb56]
%[output:7e33eb56]
    "$SHKRESP(2, 'DOM_GDP', 'SUP') < 0" %[output:7e33eb56]
    "$SHKRESP(2, 'DOM_CPI', 'SUP') > 0" %[output:7e33eb56]
%[output:7e33eb56]
    "$SHKRESP(3, 'DOM_GDP', 'SUP') < 0" %[output:7e33eb56]
    "$SHKRESP(3, 'DOM_CPI', 'SUP') > 0" %[output:7e33eb56]
] %[output:group:6bc102d0] %[output:7e33eb56]

fevdStrings = [ %[output:group:0b1814b9] %[output:5a6be391]
    "$FEVD(2, 'DOM_GDP', 'DEM') > 0" %[output:5a6be391]
] %[output:group:0b1814b9] %[output:5a6be391]
%[text] #### 
%[text] **Restriction on historical properties**
%[text] The syntax is very similar for historical shock contributions (`\\$SHKCONT`); however, for this option, the user must specify a **historical date** (instead of the simulation period) within the estimation range at which the restriction should be applied.
%[text] `"\\$SHKCONT('dateString', 'endogenousName', 'shockName') >/< X"`
contStrings = [ %[output:group:2f9b9175] %[output:279a9ae8]
    "$SHKCONT(2014-Q1, 'DOM_GDP', 'DEM') > 0" %[output:279a9ae8]
] %[output:group:2f9b9175] %[output:279a9ae8]
%[text] For the histrorical estimated shocks(\\$`SHKEST`), only the magnitude of the shock matters. Therefore, in this case, the user does not need to specify the name of the endogenous variable.
%[text] `"\\$SHKEST('dateString', 'shockName') >/< X"` 
estStrings = [ %[output:group:587ef0a2] %[output:976ae207]
    "$SHKEST(2014-Q1, 'DEM') > 0" %[output:976ae207]
] %[output:group:587ef0a2] %[output:976ae207]
%[text] 
%[text] #### Seting up the identifier (use only sign restrictions)
identVerifiables = identifier.Verifiables( ...
    signStrings, ...
    maxCandidates=50 ...
);

modelS3 = Structural(reducedForm=modelR1, identifier=identVerifiables);
modelS3.initialize();
info1 = modelS3.presample(numPresampled); %[output:9d3f5952]
modelS3.Presampled{1} %[output:92724f5a]
%[text] #### 
%[text] #### Checking transition matrices
modelS3.Presampled{1}.IdentificationDraw %[output:86b5b57a]
modelS3.Presampled{1}.IdentificationDraw.A{1,1} %[output:82d7fcf3]
modelS3.Presampled{1}.IdentificationDraw.A{2,1} %[output:9948f991]
%[text] #### 
%[text] #### Checking scaling matrix
modelS3.Presampled{1}.D %[output:8942e98b]
modelS3.Presampled{2}.D %[output:33e3e3f5]
%%
%[text] ## Impulse responses (IRF)
%[text] 
%[text] ### Cholesky
respTbl1 = modelS1.simulateResponses(); %[output:2389f831]
respTbl1 = tablex.apply(respTbl1, prctileFunc);
respTbl1 = tablex.flatten(respTbl1);

respTbl1 %[output:3a7721e3]

chartpack.responsePercentiles( ... %[output:group:8cf20de5] %[output:898bcee8]
    respTbl1, modelS1 ... %[output:898bcee8]
    , "figureTitle", "Shock response of Cholesky (percentiles)" ... %[output:898bcee8]
); %[output:group:8cf20de5] %[output:898bcee8]
%[text] ### 
%[text] ### Instant zeros

respTbl2 = modelS2.simulateResponses(); %[output:7ead9c1e]
respTbl2 = tablex.apply(respTbl2, prctileFunc);
respTbl2 = tablex.flatten(respTbl2);

respTbl2 %[output:6a3ee9b7]

chartpack.responsePercentiles( ... %[output:group:2b99d5a4] %[output:2c50e804]
    respTbl1, modelS1 ... %[output:2c50e804]
    , "figureTitle", "Shock response of instant zeros (percentiles)" ... %[output:2c50e804]
); %[output:group:2b99d5a4] %[output:2c50e804]
%[text] ### 
%[text] ### General restrictions

respTbl3 = modelS3.simulateResponses(); %[output:24c09b7b]
respTbl3 = tablex.apply(respTbl3, prctileFunc);
respTbl3 = tablex.flatten(respTbl3);

respTbl3 %[output:722ff267]

chartpack.responsePercentiles( ... %[output:group:3960f83b] %[output:9ba9bc61]
    respTbl1, modelS1 ... %[output:9ba9bc61]
    , "figureTitle", "Shock response of general restricition (percentiles)" ... %[output:9ba9bc61]
); %[output:group:3960f83b] %[output:9ba9bc61]
%%
%[text] ## **Historical shock decomposition**
%[text] 
histContTbx = modelS3.calculateContributions();

histContMedTbx = tablex.apply(histContTbx, medianFunc);

chartpack.contributionsMedian( ... %[output:group:823352a4] %[output:961bf712]
    histContMedTbx, modelS3 ... %[output:961bf712]
    , "figureTitle", "Shock contributions with Cholesky (median)" ... %[output:961bf712]
); %[output:group:823352a4] %[output:961bf712]
%%
%[text] ## **Unconditional forecast shock decomposition**
%[text] 

[uncFcastTbl1, uncFcastContribTbl1] = modelS3.forecast( ...
    fcastSpan, ...
    contributions=true ...
);


contMedTbx = tablex.apply(uncFcastContribTbl1, medianFunc);

chartpack.contributionsMedian( ... %[output:group:2d764501] %[output:92554daa]
    contMedTbx, modelS3 ... %[output:92554daa]
    , "figureTitle", "Unconditional forecast Shock contributions with Cholesky (median)" ... %[output:92554daa]
); %[output:group:2d764501] %[output:92554daa]

%%
%[text] ## **FEVD**
fevdTbx = modelS3.calculateFEVD(); %[output:7291b28c]

fevdMedTbx = tablex.apply(fevdTbx, medianFunc);

chartpack.contributionsMedian( ... %[output:group:684c4eff] %[output:691f15a6]
    fevdMedTbx, modelS3 ... %[output:691f15a6]
    , "figureTitle", "FEVD (median)" ... %[output:691f15a6]
); %[output:group:684c4eff] %[output:691f15a6]

%%
%[text] ## Conditional forecast
%[text] 
%[text] ### Setting up the conditions and the forecast plan
condDataTbl = tablex.fromFile("data/condDataTbl.xlsx");
planTbl = tablex.readConditioningPlan("data/planTbl.xlsx");
%[text] ### 
%[text] ### Setting up the forecast range 
cfcastStart = datex.shift(modelR1.Meta.EstimationEnd, 1); %The forecast starts after the estimation span.
cfcastEnd = datex.shift(modelR1.Meta.EstimationEnd, 12); 
cfcastSpan = datex.span(cfcastStart, cfcastEnd);
%[text] ### 
%[text] ### Running conditional forecast with no simulation plan
[condFcastTbl1, condFcastContribTbl1] = modelS3.conditionalForecast( ... %[output:group:4cf28a4a] %[output:9aebcb6d]
    cfcastSpan, ... %[output:9aebcb6d]
    conditions=condDataTbl, ... %[output:9aebcb6d]
    plan=[], ... %[output:9aebcb6d]
    exogenousFrom = "conditions" ... %[output:9aebcb6d]
); %[output:group:4cf28a4a] %[output:9aebcb6d]

condFcastPrctilesTbl1 = tablex.apply(condFcastTbl1, prctileFunc);
%[text] ### 
%[text] ### Running conditional forecast with simulation plan
[condFcastTbl2, condFcastContribTbl2] = modelS3.conditionalForecast( ... %[output:group:2fe7d879] %[output:0267e7c5]
    cfcastSpan, ... %[output:0267e7c5]
    conditions=condDataTbl, ... %[output:0267e7c5]
    plan=planTbl, ... %[output:0267e7c5]
    exogenousFrom = "conditions" ... %[output:0267e7c5]
); %[output:group:2fe7d879] %[output:0267e7c5]

condFcastPrctilesTbl2 = tablex.apply(condFcastTbl2, prctileFunc);
%[text] ### 
%[text] ### Visualize the conditional forecast
chartpack.conditionalForecastPercentiles( ... %[output:group:5d44efae] %[output:148c0126] %[output:4beb0e0a] %[output:16a3e984]
    condFcastPrctilesTbl1, modelS3 ... %[output:148c0126] %[output:4beb0e0a] %[output:16a3e984]
    , "figureTitle", "Conditional forecast w/o plan (percentiles)" ... %[output:148c0126] %[output:4beb0e0a] %[output:16a3e984]
); %[output:group:5d44efae] %[output:148c0126] %[output:4beb0e0a] %[output:16a3e984]

